of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Cantilupe was born in 1151. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Henry de Longchamp Sheriff of Herefordshire. She died in 1246, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, at the age of 95, and was buried in Longueville, Jersey."},"et":{"1151–1246":"1151–1246","1160–1212":"1160–1212","1177–1210":"1177–1210","1179–1220":"1179–1220","1210–1264":"1210–1264","1246":"1246","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1177":"1177","1210":"1210","1220":"1220","1264":"1264","1186":"1186","1151":"1151","um 1190":"umbes 1190","1160":"1160","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Longueville, Jersey, England":"Longueville, Jersey saar","Beaudesert Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Beaudesert, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wilton, Herefordshire, Inglaterra, United Kingdom":"Wilton, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Wilton Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Wilton, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kin